Incarceration Rates in Relation to Race

Looking at the data presented on the Vera Institute for Justice regarding Incarceration Trends, it is clearly seen that there are racial disparities present in jail rates. On the website there are very detailed reports on the incarcerations of different races, having a specific emphasis on people of color- and black people particularly, in aims to prove how this is a result of the criminal system treating black people more harshly in every sector of the legal process. These racial disparities cause harms beyond longer jail times, but also lead towards disproportionate economic, health, and social problems for communities of color.

The aims of this report is to dissect the prevalent issue of racism present in incarceration rates, and the data selected is to prove that there are inequalities and harsher jail times, and treatments pushed onto people of color, and black people in particular are much more extensive.

Insights

Oregon and California were two regions of interest for me because California is a majority-minority state, and Oregon is known as a more rural state with a higher population of White people. I wanted to compare two states that were located close to each-other, but opposites in terms of size and demographics. After computing this data for both Oregon and California, it was unsurprising to see that for the most recent dates of incarcerations, which was in 2018, the proportion of black/white and latinx/white in California did not have a huge gap, (2.82 v.s. 5.28), this is not shocking because Latinx and black populations are amongst the most profiled races by law enforcement, and face much harsher punishment for crimes due to this. The gap for the overall ratio is much larger, with the prop_ca_black_white2 being roughly 3.4 and prop_ca_latinx_white2 being roughly 19.7. With the latinx/white proportion being almost 6 times larger than the black/white, It is unfortunate to see that the level of incarceration has increased over the years, as it is evident that criminal justice reform is necessary. On the other hand, when looking at Oregon, for 2018 incarcerations, there was not a huge gap between the proportion of black/white and Latinx/white, (0.81 v.s. 1.04), this was not shocking to me since Oregon is much smaller in population in comparison to California, therefore having less of a black and Latinx community. It was relieving to see that there was not a huge increase in incarceration when compared to the overall proportion for Oregon, (0.81 v.s. 2). This also raises the question on if racial disparities in the justice system are more present in highly populated areas of people of color.

Black Jail Incarceration Rates Nationwide by the Year

Evidently, incarceration rates of black individuals has only increased since the beginning of data being collected in 1988. The data is skewed to the left, with the peak occurring in 2008, where there was the highest incarceration rate. Luckily, since 2008, the rates have slowly decreased, however it is not a significant change, indicating that reform is still very much necessary.

Jail Population of Latinx v.s. White People

This graph comparing the Latinx jail population (yellow), to the White jail population (purple), clearly illustrates the immense gap between imprisoned BIPOC and White people. The gap is increasingly prevalent in 1003, where there is a huge peak of the number of people who identify as Latinx in jail. I included this graph in order to help prove the unfortunate, yet true fact that BIPOC are jailed at higher rates than their white counterparts, and face harsher punishment for crimes, increasing the totals of POC in jails.

Black Jail Population in Washington

The inclusion of a graph of Washington, is because as an individual who had lived in Washington her entire life, I wanted to analyze the trends and where the counties with the highest populations of incarcerated black individuals are located. This graph is color coded, with counties that have the red hues being where the highest population of black incarcerations were which was Yakima County and Lincoln County, and Adams County and lowest populations being tinted bright blue, which Whitman County had the least.

Black Jail Population in California

The inclusion of the California map, was to also analyze what counties with the highest populations of incarcerated black individuals in California were. Again, this graph is color coded, with counties that are tinted with red hues being where the highest populations of incarcerated black individuals are located, which was Trinity County, and the lowest population of incarcerated black individuals being tinted bright blue, which was Del Norte County and Lassen County.
